[src:finite-element-method/basis-function] In mathematics, a **basis function** is an element of a particular basis for a function space.
[src:finite-element-method/basis-function] Every function in the function space can be represented as a linear combination of basis functions.
[src:finite-element-method/basis-function] In finite-dimensional vector spaces this representation is purely algebraic and involves only finitely many basis functions, whereas in infinite-dimensional settings it typically takes the form of an infinite series whose convergence depends on the topology of the space.
[src:finite-element-method/basis-function] This basis is used in Taylor series, amongst others.
[src:finite-element-method/basis-function] The monomial basis also forms a basis for the vector space of polynomials.
[src:finite-element-method/basis-function] After all, every polynomial can be written as $a_{0}+a_{1}x^{1}+a_{2}x^{2}+\cdots +a_{n}x^{n}$ for some $n\in \mathbb {N}$ , which is a linear combination of monomials.
[src:finite-element-method/basis-function] Sines and cosines form an (orthonormal) Schauder basis for square-integrable functions on a bounded domain.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] FEM is a general numerical method for solving partial differential equations in two- or three-space variables (i.e., some boundary value problems).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] There are also studies about using FEM to solve high-dimensional problems.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] To solve a problem, FEM subdivides a large system into smaller, simpler parts called **finite elements**.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] This is achieved by a particular space discretization in the space dimensions, which is implemented by the construction of a mesh of the object: the numerical domain for the solution that has a finite number of points.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] FEM formulation of a boundary value problem finally results in a system of algebraic equations.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The method approximates the unknown function over the domain.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The simple equations that model these finite elements are then assembled into a larger system of equations that models the entire problem.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] FEM then approximates a solution by minimizing an associated error function via the calculus of variations.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Studying or analyzing a phenomenon with FEM is often referred to as **finite element analysis** (FEA).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] by the coil (rectangular area on the right).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] , as indicated by the scale in the inset legend, red being high amplitude.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The area inside the cylinder is low amplitude (dark blue, with widely spaced lines of magnetic flux), which suggests that the shield is performing as it was designed to.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Systematically recombining all sets of element equations into a global system of equations for the final calculation.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The global system of equations uses known solution techniques and can be calculated from the initial values of the original problem to obtain a numerical answer.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In the first step above, the element equations are simple equations that locally approximate the original complex equations to be studied, where the original equations are often partial differential equations (PDEs).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] To explain the approximation of this process, FEM is commonly introduced as a special case of the Galerkin method.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The process, in mathematical language, is to construct an integral of the inner product of the residual and the weight functions; then, set the integral to zero.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In simple terms, it is a procedure that minimizes the approximation error by fitting trial functions into the PDE.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The residual is the error caused by the trial functions, and the weight functions are polynomial approximation functions that project the residual.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] These equation sets are element equations.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] They are linear if the underlying PDE is linear and vice versa.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Algebraic equation sets that arise in the steady-state problems are solved using numerical linear algebraic methods.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In contrast, ordinary differential equation sets that occur in the transient problems are solved by numerical integrations using standard techniques such as Euler's method or the Runge–Kutta methods.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In the second step above, a global system of equations is generated from the element equations by transforming coordinates from the subdomains' local nodes to the domain's global nodes.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] This spatial transformation includes appropriate orientation adjustments as applied in relation to the reference coordinate system.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The process is often carried out using FEM software with coordinate data generated from the subdomains.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The practical application of FEM is known as finite element analysis (FEA).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] FEA, as applied in engineering, is a computational tool for performing engineering analysis.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] It includes the use of mesh generation techniques for dividing a complex problem into smaller elements, as well as the use of software coded with a FEM algorithm.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] FEA may be used for analyzing problems over complicated domains (e.g., cars and oil pipelines) when the domain changes (e.g., during a solid-state reaction with a moving boundary), when the desired precision varies over the entire domain, or when the solution lacks smoothness.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] FEA simulations provide a valuable resource, as they remove multiple instances of creating and testing complex prototypes for various high-fidelity situations.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] For example, in a frontal crash simulation, it is possible to increase prediction accuracy in important areas, like the front of the car, and reduce it in the rear of the car, thus reducing the cost of the simulation.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Another example would be in numerical weather prediction, where it is more important to have accurate predictions over developing highly nonlinear phenomena, such as tropical cyclones in the atmosphere or eddies in the ocean, rather than relatively calm areas.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] A clear, detailed, and practical presentation of this approach can be found in the textbook *The Finite Element Method for Engineers*.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] While it is difficult to quote the date of the invention of FEM, the method originated from the need to solve complex elasticity and structural analysis problems in civil and aeronautical engineering.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Its development can be traced back to work by Alexander Hrennikoff and Richard Courant in the early 1940s.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In the USSR, the introduction of the practical application of FEM is usually connected with Leonard Oganesyan.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] It was also independently rediscovered in China by Feng Kang in the late 1950s and early 1960s, based on the computations of dam constructions, where it was called the "finite difference method" based on variation principles.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Although the approaches used by these pioneers are different, they share one essential characteristic: the mesh discretization of a continuous domain into a set of discrete sub-domains, usually called elements.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Hrennikoff's work discretizes the domain by using a lattice analogy, while Courant's approach divides the domain into finite triangular sub-regions to solve second-order elliptic partial differential equations that arise from the problem of the torsion of a cylinder.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Courant's contribution was evolutionary, drawing on a large body of earlier results for PDEs developed by Lord Rayleigh, Walther Ritz, and Boris Galerkin.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The application of FEM gained momentum in the 1960s and 1970s due to the developments of J.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Argyris and his co-workers at the University of Stuttgart; R.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Clough and his co-workers at University of California Berkeley; O.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Zienkiewicz and his co-workers Ernest Hinton, Bruce Irons, and others at Swansea University; Philippe G.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Ciarlet at the University of Paris 6; and Richard Gallagher and his co-workers at Cornell University.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] During this period, additional impetus was provided by the available open-source FEM programs.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] NASA sponsored the original version of NASTRAN.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] University of California Berkeley made the finite element programs SAP IV and, later, OpenSees widely available.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In Norway, the ship classification society Det Norske Veritas (now DNV GL) developed Sesam in 1969 for use in the analysis of ships.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] A rigorous mathematical basis for FEM was provided in 1973 with a publication by Gilbert Strang and George Fix.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The method has since been generalized for the numerical modeling of physical systems in a wide variety of engineering disciplines, such as electromagnetism, heat transfer, and fluid dynamics.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] A finite element method is characterized by a variational formulation, a discretization strategy, one or more solution algorithms, and post-processing procedures.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Examples of the variational formulation are the Galerkin method, the discontinuous Galerkin method, mixed methods, etc.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] A discretization strategy is understood to mean a clearly defined set of procedures that cover (a) the creation of finite element meshes, (b) the definition of basis function on reference elements (also called shape functions), and (c) the mapping of reference elements onto the elements of the mesh.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Examples of discretization strategies are the h-version, p-version, hp-version, x-FEM, isogeometric analysis, etc.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Each discretization strategy has certain advantages and disadvantages.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] A reasonable criterion in selecting a discretization strategy is to realize nearly optimal performance for the broadest set of mathematical models in a particular model class.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Various numerical solution algorithms can be classified into two broad categories; direct and iterative solvers.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] These algorithms are designed to exploit the sparsity of matrices that depend on the variational formulation and discretization strategy choices.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Post-processing procedures are designed to extract the data of interest from a finite element solution.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] To meet the requirements of solution verification, postprocessors need to provide for *a posteriori* error estimation in terms of the quantities of interest.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] When the errors of approximation are larger than what is considered acceptable, then the discretization has to be changed either by an automated adaptive process or by the action of the analyst.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Some very efficient postprocessors provide for the realization of superconvergence.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The following two problems demonstrate the finite element method.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] P1 is a one-dimensional problem ${\text{ P1 }}:{\begin{cases}u''(x)=f(x){\text{ in }}(0,1),\\u(0)=u(1)=0,\end{cases}}$ where f is given, u is an unknown function of x , and $u''$ is the second derivative of u with respect to x .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] where $\Omega$ is a connected open region in the $(x,y)$ plane whose boundary $\partial \Omega$ is nice (e.g., a smooth manifold or a polygon), and $u_{xx}$ and $u_{yy}$ denote the second derivatives with respect to x and y , respectively.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The problem P1 can be solved directly by computing antiderivatives.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] However, this method of solving the boundary value problem (BVP) works only when there is one spatial dimension.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] It does not generalize to higher-dimensional problems or problems like $u+V''=f$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] For this reason, we will develop the finite element method for P1 and outline its generalization to P2.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Our explanation will proceed in two steps, which mirror two essential steps one must take to solve a boundary value problem (BVP) using the FEM.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] After this second step, we have concrete formulae for a large but finite-dimensional linear problem whose solution will approximately solve the original BVP.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] This finite-dimensional problem is then implemented on a computer.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The first step is to convert P1 and P2 into their equivalent weak formulations.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Conversely, if u with $u(0)=u(1)=0$ satisfies (1) for every smooth function $v(x)$ then one may show that this u will solve P1.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The proof is easier for twice continuously differentiable u (mean value theorem) but may be proved in a distributional sense as well.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] where we have used the assumption that $v(0)=v(1)=0$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] where $\nabla$ denotes the gradient and $\cdot$ denotes the dot product in the two-dimensional plane.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Once more $\,\!\phi$ can be turned into an inner product on a suitable space $H_{0}^{1}(\Omega )$ of once differentiable functions of $\Omega$ that are zero on $\partial \Omega$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] We have also assumed that $v\in H_{0}^{1}(\Omega )$ (see Sobolev spaces).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The existence and uniqueness of the solution can also be shown.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] We can loosely think of $H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$ to be the absolutely continuous functions of $(0,1)$ that are 0 at $x=0$ and $x=1$ (see Sobolev spaces).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Such functions are (weakly) once differentiable, and it turns out that the symmetric bilinear map $\!\,\phi$ then defines an inner product which turns $H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$ into a Hilbert space (a detailed proof is nontrivial).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] On the other hand, the left-hand-side $\int _{0}^{1}f(x)v(x)dx$ is also an inner product, this time on the Lp space $L^{2}(0,1)$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] An application of the Riesz representation theorem for Hilbert spaces shows that there is a unique u solving (2) and, therefore, P1.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] This solution is a-priori only a member of $H_{0}^{1}(0,1)$ , but using elliptic regularity, will be smooth if f is.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] P1 and P2 are ready to be discretized, which leads to a common sub-problem (3).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] where V is a finite-dimensional subspace of $H_{0}^{1}$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] There are many possible choices for V (one possibility leads to the spectral method).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] However, we take V as a space of piecewise polynomial functions for the finite element method.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Observe that functions in V are not differentiable according to the elementary definition of calculus.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Indeed, if $v\in V$ then the derivative is typically not defined at any $x=x_{k}$ , $k=1,\ldots ,n$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] However, the derivative exists at every other value of x , and one can use this derivative for integration by parts.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] We need V to be a set of functions of $\Omega$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] One hopes that as the underlying triangular mesh becomes finer and finer, the solution of the discrete problem (3) will, in some sense, converge to the solution of the original boundary value problem P2.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] To measure this mesh fineness, the triangulation is indexed by a real-valued parameter $h>0$ which one takes to be very small.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] This parameter will be related to the largest or average triangle size in the triangulation.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] As we refine the triangulation, the space of piecewise linear functions V must also change with h .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] For this reason, one often reads $V_{h}$ instead of V in the literature.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Since we do not perform such an analysis, we will not use this notation.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] To complete the discretization, we must select a basis of V .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] for $k=1,\dots ,n$ ; this basis is a shifted and scaled tent function.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] For the two-dimensional case, we choose again one basis function $v_{k}$ per vertex $x_{k}$ of the triangulation of the planar region $\Omega$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The function $v_{k}$ is the unique function of V whose value is 1 at $x_{k}$ and zero at every $x_{j},\;j\neq k$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Depending on the author, the word "element" in the "finite element method" refers to the domain's triangles, the piecewise linear basis function, or both.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] So, for instance, an author interested in curved domains might replace the triangles with curved primitives and so might describe the elements as being curvilinear.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] On the other hand, some authors replace "piecewise linear" with "piecewise quadratic" or even "piecewise polynomial".
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The author might then say "higher order element" instead of "higher degree polynomial".
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The finite element method is not restricted to triangles (tetrahedra in 3-d or higher-order simplexes in multidimensional spaces).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Still, it can be defined on quadrilateral subdomains (hexahedra, prisms, or pyramids in 3-d, and so on).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Higher-order shapes (curvilinear elements) can be defined with polynomial and even non-polynomial shapes (e.g., ellipse or circle).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Examples of methods that use higher degree piecewise polynomial basis functions are the hp-FEM and spectral FEM.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] (The matrix containing $\langle v_{j},v_{k}\rangle$ in the $(j,k)$ location is known as the Gramian matrix.) In the one dimensional case, the support of $v_{k}$ is the interval $[x_{k-1},x_{k+1}]$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Hence, the integrands of $\langle v_{j},v_{k}\rangle$ and $\phi (v_{j},v_{k})$ are identically zero whenever $|j-k|>1$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Similarly, in the planar case, if $x_{j}$ and $x_{k}$ do not share an edge of the triangulation, then the integrals $\int _{\Omega }v_{j}v_{k}\,ds$ and $\int _{\Omega }\nabla v_{j}\cdot \nabla v_{k}\,ds$ are both zero.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] As we have discussed before, most of the entries of L and M are zero because the basis functions $v_{k}$ have small support.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] So we now have to solve a linear system in the unknown $\mathbf {u}$ where most of the entries of the matrix L , which we need to invert, are zero.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Such matrices are known as sparse matrices, and there are efficient solvers for such problems (much more efficient than actually inverting the matrix.) In addition, L is symmetric and positive definite, so a technique such as the conjugate gradient method is favored.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] For problems that are not too large, sparse LU decompositions and Cholesky decompositions still work well.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] For instance, MATLAB's backslash operator (which uses sparse LU, sparse Cholesky, and other factorization methods) can be sufficient for meshes with a hundred thousand vertices.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The matrix L is usually referred to as the stiffness matrix, while the matrix M is dubbed the mass matrix.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In general, the finite element method is characterized by the following process.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Separate consideration is the smoothness of the basis functions.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] For second-order elliptic boundary value problems, piecewise polynomial basis function that is merely continuous suffice (i.e., the derivatives are discontinuous.) For higher-order partial differential equations, one must use smoother basis functions.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] For instance, for a fourth-order problem such as $u_{xxxx}+u_{yyyy}=f$ , one may use piecewise quadratic basis functions that are $C^{1}$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Another consideration is the relation of the finite-dimensional space V to its infinite-dimensional counterpart in the examples above $H_{0}^{1}$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] A conforming element method is one in which space V is a subspace of the element space for the continuous problem.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] If this condition is not satisfied, we obtain a nonconforming element method, an example of which is the space of piecewise linear functions over the mesh, which are continuous at each edge midpoint.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Since these functions are generally discontinuous along the edges, this finite-dimensional space is not a subspace of the original $H_{0}^{1}$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Typically, one has an algorithm for subdividing a given mesh.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Under specific hypotheses (for instance, if the domain is convex), a piecewise polynomial of order d method will have an error of order $p=d+1$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] If instead of making *h* smaller, one increases the degree of the polynomials used in the basis function, one has a *p*-method.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] If one combines these two refinement types, one obtains an *hp*-method (hp-FEM).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In the hp-FEM, the polynomial degrees can vary from element to element.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] High-order methods with large uniform *p* are called spectral finite element methods (SFEM).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] These are not to be confused with spectral methods.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] For vector partial differential equations, the basis functions may take values in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The Applied Element Method or AEM combines features of both FEM and Discrete element method or (DEM).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Yang and Lui introduced the Augmented-Finite Element Method, whose goal was to model the weak and strong discontinuities without needing extra DoFs, as PuM stated.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The Cut Finite Element Approach was developed in 2014.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The generalized finite element method (GFEM) uses local spaces consisting of functions, not necessarily polynomials, that reflect the available information on the unknown solution and thus ensure good local approximation.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Then a partition of unity is used to "bond" these spaces together to form the approximating subspace.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The effectiveness of GFEM has been shown when applied to problems with domains having complicated boundaries, problems with micro-scales, and problems with boundary layers.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The mixed finite element method is a type of finite element method in which extra independent variables are introduced as nodal variables during the discretization of a partial differential equation problem.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The hp-FEM combines adaptively elements with variable size *h* and polynomial degree *p* to achieve exceptionally fast, exponential convergence rates.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The hpk-FEM combines adaptively elements with variable size *h*, polynomial degree of the local approximations *p*, and global differentiability of the local approximations (*k*-1) to achieve the best convergence rates.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The extended finite element method (XFEM) is a numerical technique based on the generalized finite element method (GFEM) and the partition of unity method (PUM).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] It extends the classical finite element method by enriching the solution space for solutions to differential equations with discontinuous functions.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Extended finite element methods enrich the approximation space to naturally reproduce the challenging feature associated with the problem of interest: the discontinuity, singularity, boundary layer, etc.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] It was shown that for some problems, such an embedding of the problem's feature into the approximation space can significantly improve convergence rates and accuracy.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] XFEM has also been implemented in codes like Altair Radios, ASTER, Morfeo, and Abaqus.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] It is increasingly being adopted by other commercial finite element software, with a few plugins and actual core implementations available (ANSYS, SAMCEF, OOFELIE, etc.).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The introduction of the scaled boundary finite element method (SBFEM) came from Song and Wolf (1997).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The SBFEM has been one of the most profitable contributions in the area of numerical analysis of fracture mechanics problems.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] It is a semi-analytical fundamental-solutionless method combining the advantages of finite element formulations and procedures and boundary element discretization.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] However, unlike the boundary element method, no fundamental differential solution is required.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The S-FEM, Smoothed Finite Element Methods, is a particular class of numerical simulation algorithms for the simulation of physical phenomena.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] It was developed by combining mesh-free methods with the finite element method.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Spectral element methods combine the geometric flexibility of finite elements and the acute accuracy of spectral methods.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Spectral methods are the approximate solution of weak-form partial equations based on high-order Lagrangian interpolants and used only with certain quadrature rules.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Loubignac iteration is an iterative method in finite element methods.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The crystal plasticity finite element method (CPFEM) is an advanced numerical tool developed by Franz Roters.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Metals can be regarded as crystal aggregates, which behave anisotropy under deformation, such as abnormal stress and strain localization.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] CPFEM, based on the slip (shear strain rate), can calculate dislocation, crystal orientation, and other texture information to consider crystal anisotropy during the routine.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] It has been applied in the numerical study of material deformation, surface roughness, fractures, etc.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The virtual element method (VEM), introduced by Beirão da Veiga et al.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] (2013) as an extension of mimetic finite difference (MFD) methods, is a generalization of the standard finite element method for arbitrary element geometries.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] This allows admission of general polygons (or polyhedra in 3D) that are highly irregular and non-convex in shape.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The name *virtual* derives from the fact that knowledge of the local shape function basis is not required and is, in fact, never explicitly calculated.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Some types of finite element methods (conforming, nonconforming, mixed finite element methods) are particular cases of the gradient discretization method (GDM).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Hence the convergence properties of the GDM, which are established for a series of problems (linear and nonlinear elliptic problems, linear, nonlinear, and degenerate parabolic problems), hold as well for these particular FEMs.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The finite difference method (FDM) is an alternative way of approximating solutions of PDEs.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Generally, FEM is the method of choice in all types of analysis in structural mechanics (i.e., solving for deformation and stresses in solid bodies or dynamics of structures).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In contrast, computational fluid dynamics (CFD) tend to use FDM or other methods like finite volume method (FVM).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] CFD problems usually require discretization of the problem into a large number of cells/gridpoints (millions and more).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Therefore the cost of the solution favors simpler, lower-order approximation within each cell.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] This is especially true for 'external flow' problems, like airflow around the car, airplane, or weather simulation.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Another method used for approximating solutions to a partial differential equation is the Fast Fourier Transform (FFT), where the solution is approximated by a Fourier series computed using the FFT.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] For approximating the mechanical response of materials under stress, FFT is often much faster, but FEM may be more accurate.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] One example of the respective advantages of the two methods is in simulation of rolling a sheet of aluminum (an FCC metal), and drawing a wire of tungsten (a BCC metal).
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] This simulation did not have a sophisticated shape update algorithm for the FFT method.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In both cases, the FFT method was more than 10 times as fast as FEM, but in the wire drawing simulation, where there were large deformations in grains, the FEM method was much more accurate.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In the sheet rolling simulation, the results of the two methods were similar.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] FFT has a larger speed advantage in cases where the boundary conditions are given in the materials strain, and loses some of its efficiency in cases where the stress is used to apply the boundary conditions, as more iterations of the method are needed.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The FE and FFT methods can also be combined in a voxel based method (2) to simulate deformation in materials, where the FE method is used for the macroscale stress and deformation, and the FFT method is used on the microscale to deal with the effects of microscale on the mechanical response.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Unlike FEM, FFT methods' similarities to image processing methods means that an actual image of the microstructure from a microscope can be input to the solver to get a more accurate stress response.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Using a real image with FFT avoids meshing the microstructure, which would be required if using FEM simulation of the microstructure, and might be difficult.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Because Fourier approximations are inherently periodic, FFT can only be used in cases of periodic microstructure, but this is common in real materials.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] FFT can also be combined with FEM methods by using Fourier components as the variational basis for approximating the fields inside an element, which can take advantage of the speed of FFT based solvers.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Various specializations under the umbrella of the mechanical engineering discipline (such as aeronautical, biomechanical, and automotive industries) commonly use integrated FEM in the design and development of their products.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Several modern FEM packages include specific components such as thermal, electromagnetic, fluid, and structural working environments.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In a structural simulation, FEM helps tremendously in producing stiffness and strength visualizations and minimizing weight, materials, and costs.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] This powerful design tool has significantly improved both the standard of engineering designs and the design process methodology in many industrial applications.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] The introduction of FEM has substantially decreased the time to take products from concept to the production line.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Testing and development have been accelerated primarily through improved initial prototype designs using FEM.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In summary, benefits of FEM include increased accuracy, enhanced design and better insight into critical design parameters, virtual prototyping, fewer hardware prototypes, a faster and less expensive design cycle, increased productivity, and increased revenue.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] In the 1990s FEM was proposed for use in stochastic modeling for numerically solving probability models and later for reliability assessment.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] FEM is widely applied for approximating differential equations that describe physical systems.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] This method is very popular in the community of Computational fluid dynamics, and there are many applications for solving Navier–Stokes equations with FEM.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Recently, the application of FEM has been increasing in the researches of computational plasma.
[src:finite-element-method/finite-element-method] Promising numerical results using FEM for Magnetohydrodynamics, Vlasov equation, and Schrödinger equation have been proposed.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] They are named after the Soviet mathematician Boris Galerkin.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Here, $a(\cdot ,\cdot )$ is a bilinear form (the exact requirements on $a(\cdot ,\cdot )$ will be specified later) and f is a bounded linear functional on V .
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Notice that the equation has remained unchanged and only the spaces have changed.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Reducing the problem to a finite-dimensional vector subspace allows us to numerically compute $u_{n}$ as a finite linear combination of the basis vectors in $V_{n}$ .
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] The key property of the Galerkin approach is that the error is orthogonal to the chosen subspaces.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Since $V_{n}\subset V$ , we can use $v_{n}$ as a test vector in the original equation.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Since the aim of Galerkin's method is the production of a linear system of equations, we build its matrix form, which can be used to compute the solution algorithmically.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Due to the definition of the matrix entries, the matrix of the Galerkin equation is symmetric if and only if the bilinear form $a(\cdot ,\cdot )$ is symmetric.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] While this is not really a restriction of Galerkin methods, the application of the standard theory becomes much simpler.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Furthermore, a Petrov–Galerkin method may be required in the nonsymmetric case.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] The analysis of these methods proceeds in two steps.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] First, we will show that the Galerkin equation is a well-posed problem in the sense of Hadamard and therefore admits a unique solution.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] In the second step, we study the quality of approximation of the Galerkin solution $u_{n}$ .
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] By the Lax-Milgram theorem (see weak formulation), these two conditions imply well-posedness of the original problem in weak formulation.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] All norms in the following sections will be norms for which the above inequalities hold (these norms are often called an energy norm).
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Since $V_{n}\subset V$ , boundedness and ellipticity of the bilinear form apply to $V_{n}$ .
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Therefore, the well-posedness of the Galerkin problem is actually inherited from the well-posedness of the original problem.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] This means, that up to the constant $C/c$ , the Galerkin solution $u_{n}$ is as close to the original solution u as any other vector in $V_{n}$ .
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] In particular, it will be sufficient to study approximation by spaces $V_{n}$ , completely forgetting about the equation being solved.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Dividing by $c\|u-u_{n}\|$ and taking the infimum over all possible $v_{n}$ yields the lemma.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] For simplicity of presentation in the section above we have assumed that the bilinear form $a(u,v)$ is symmetric and positive-definite, which implies that it is a scalar product and the expression ${\textstyle \|u\|_{a}={\sqrt {a(u,u)}}}$ is actually a valid vector norm, called the *energy norm*.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Under these assumptions one can easily prove in addition Galerkin's best approximation property in the energy norm.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Reddy studied the application of the Galerkin method to stepped structures.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] They showed that the generalized function, namely unit-step function, Dirac’s delta function, and the doublet function are needed for obtaining accurate results.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] The approach is usually credited to Boris Galerkin.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] The method was explained to the Western reader by Hencky and Duncan among others.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Its convergence was studied by Mikhlin and Leipholz Its coincidence with Fourier method was illustrated by Elishakoff et al.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Its equivalence to Ritz's method for conservative problems was shown by Singer.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Gander and Wanner showed how Ritz and Galerkin methods led to the modern finite element method.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] One hundred years of method's development was discussed by Repin.
[src:finite-element-method/galerkin-method] Elishakoff, Kaplunov and Kaplunov show that the Galerkin’s method was not developed by Ritz, contrary to the Timoshenko’s statements.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Meshes are used for rendering to a computer screen and for physical simulation such as finite element analysis or computational fluid dynamics.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] We can simulate the strength of the bridge, or draw it on a computer screen, by performing calculations on each triangle and calculating the interactions between triangles.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] A major distinction is between structured and unstructured meshing.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In structured meshing the mesh is a regular lattice, such as an array, with implied connectivity between elements.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In unstructured meshing, elements may be connected to each other in irregular patterns, and more complicated domains can be captured.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] This page is primarily about unstructured meshes.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] While a mesh may be a triangulation, the process of meshing is distinguished from point set triangulation in that meshing includes the freedom to add vertices not present in the input.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] "Facetting" (triangulating) CAD models for drafting has the same freedom to add vertices, but the goal is to represent the shape accurately using as few triangles as possible and the shape of individual triangles is not important.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Computer graphics renderings of textures and realistic lighting conditions use meshes instead.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Many mesh generation software is coupled to a CAD system defining its input, and simulation software for taking its output.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The input can vary greatly but common forms are Solid modeling, Geometric modeling, NURBS, B-rep, STL or a point cloud.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Mesh faces (cells, entities) have different names depending on their dimension and the context in which the mesh will be used.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In finite elements, the highest-dimensional mesh entities are called "elements," "edges" are 1D and "nodes" are 0D.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] If the elements are 3D, then the 2D entities are "faces." In computational geometry, the 0D points are called vertices.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Many meshing techniques are built on the principles of the Delaunay triangulation, together with rules for adding vertices, such as Ruppert's algorithm.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] A distinguishing feature is that an initial coarse mesh of the entire space is formed, then vertices and triangles are added.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In contrast, advancing front algorithms start from the domain boundary, and add elements incrementally filling up the interior.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] A special class of advancing front techniques creates thin boundary layers of elements for fluid flow.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In structured mesh generation the entire mesh is a lattice graph, such as a regular grid of squares.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In block-structured meshing, the domain is divided into large subregions, each of which is a structured mesh.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Some direct methods start with a block-structured mesh and then move the mesh to conform to the input; see Automatic Hex-Mesh Generation based on polycube.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Another direct method is to cut the structured cells by the domain boundary; see sculpt based on Marching cubes.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Some types of meshes are much more difficult to create than others.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Simplicial meshes tend to be easier than cubical meshes.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] An important category is generating a hex mesh conforming to a fixed quad surface mesh; a research subarea is studying the existence and generation of meshes of specific small configurations, such as the tetragonal trapezohedron.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Because of the difficulty of this problem, the existence of combinatorial hex meshes has been studied apart from the problem of generating good geometric realizations; see Combinatorial Techniques for Hexahedral Mesh Generation.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] While known algorithms generate simplicial meshes with guaranteed minimum quality, such guarantees are rare for cubical meshes, and many popular implementations generate inverted (inside-out) hexes from some inputs.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Meshes are often created in serial on workstations, even when subsequent calculations over the mesh will be done in parallel on super-computers.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] This is both because of the limitation that most mesh generators are interactive, and because mesh generation runtime is typically insignificant compared to solver time.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] However, if the mesh is too large to fit in the memory of a single serial machine, or the mesh must be changed (adapted) during the simulation, meshing is done in parallel.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The grid generation by algebraic methods is based on mathematical interpolation function.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] It is done by using known functions in one, two or three dimensions taking arbitrary shaped regions.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The computational domain might not be rectangular, but for the sake of simplicity, the domain is taken to be rectangular.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The main advantage of the methods is that they provide explicit control of physical grid shape and spacing.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The simplest procedure that may be used to produce boundary fitted computational mesh is the normalization transformation.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] where $y_{\max }$ denotes the y-coordinate of the nozzle wall.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] For given values of ( $\xi$ , $\eta$ ), the values of ( x , y ) can be easily recovered.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Like algebraic methods, differential equation methods are also used to generate grids.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The advantage of using the partial differential equations (PDEs) is that the solution of grid generating equations can be exploited to generate the mesh.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Grid construction can be done using all three classes of partial differential equations.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Elliptic PDEs generally have very smooth solutions leading to smooth contours.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Using its smoothness as an advantage Laplace's equations can preferably be used because the Jacobian found out to be positive as a result of maximum principle for harmonic functions.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] After extensive work done by Crowley (1962) and Winslow (1966) on PDEs by transforming physical domain into computational plane while mapping using Poisson's equation, Thompson et al.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] (1974) have worked extensively on elliptic PDEs to generate grids.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] where, $(\xi ,\eta )$ are the co-ordinates in the computational domain, while P and Q are responsible for point spacing within D.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] These systems of equations are solved in the computational plane on uniformly spaced grid which provides us with the $(x,y)$ co-ordinates of each point in physical space.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The advantage of using elliptic PDEs is the solution linked to them is smooth and the resulting grid is smooth.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] But, specification of P and Q becomes a difficult task thus adding it to its disadvantages.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Moreover, the grid has to be computed after each time step which adds up to computational time.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] This grid generation scheme is generally applicable to problems with open domains consistent with the type of PDE describing the physical problem.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The advantage associated with hyperbolic PDEs is that the governing equations need to be solved only once for generating grid.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The initial point distribution along with the approximate boundary conditions forms the required input and the solution is the then marched outward.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Steger and Sorenson (1980) proposed a volume orthogonality method that uses Hyperbolic PDEs for mesh generation.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] where I represents the area in physical space for a given area in computational space.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The problem associated with such system of equations is the specification of I .
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Poor selection of I may lead to shock and discontinuous propagation of this information throughout the mesh.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] While mesh being orthogonal is generated very rapidly which comes out as an advantage with this method.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The solving technique is similar to that of hyperbolic PDEs by advancing the solution away from the initial data surface satisfying the boundary conditions at the end.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Nakamura (1982) and Edwards (1985) developed the basic ideas for parabolic grid generation.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The idea uses either of Laplace or the Poisson's equation and especially treating the parts which controls elliptic behavior.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The initial values are given as the coordinates of the point along the surface $\eta =0$ and the advancing the solutions to the outer surface of the object satisfying the boundary conditions along $\xi$ edges.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The control of the grid spacing has not been suggested until now.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Nakamura and Edwards, grid control was accomplished using non uniform spacing.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The parabolic grid generation shows an advantage over the hyperbolic grid generation that, no shocks or discontinuities occur and the grid is relatively smooth.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The specifications of initial values and selection of step size to control the grid points is however time-consuming, but these techniques can be effective when familiarity and experience is gained.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] This method includes a technique that minimizes grid smoothness, orthogonality and volume variation.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] This method forms mathematical platform to solve grid generation problems.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In this method an alternative grid is generated by a new mesh after each iteration and computing the grid speed using backward difference method.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] This technique is a powerful one with a disadvantage that effort is required to solve the equations related to grid.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Further work needed to be done to minimize the integrals that will reduce the CPU time.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The main importance of this scheme is that it provides a method that will generate the grid automatically.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Using this method, grids are segmented into blocks according to the surface of the element and a structure is provided to ensure appropriate connectivity.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] To interpret the data flow solver is used.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] When an unstructured scheme is employed, the main interest is to fulfill the demand of the user and a grid generator is used to accomplish this task.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The information storage in structured scheme is cell to cell instead of grid to grid and hence the more memory space is needed.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Due to random cell location, the solver efficiency in unstructured is less as compared to the structured scheme.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Some points are needed to be kept in mind at the time of grid construction.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The grid point with high resolution creates difficulty for both structured and unstructured.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] For example, in case of boundary layer, structured scheme produces elongated grid in the direction of flow.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] On the other hand, unstructured grids require a higher cell density in the boundary layer because the cell needs to be as equilateral as possible to avoid errors.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] We must identify what information is required to identify the cell and all the neighbors of the cell in the computational mesh.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] We can choose to locate the arbitrary points anywhere we want for the unstructured grid.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] A point insertion scheme is used to insert the points independently and the cell connectivity is determined.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] This suggests that the point be identified as they are inserted.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Logic for establishing new connectivity is determined once the points are inserted.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Data that form grid point that identifies grid cell are needed.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] As each cell is formed it is numbered and the points are sorted.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In addition the neighbor cell information is needed.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] A problem in solving partial differential equations using previous methods is that the grid is constructed and the points are distributed in the physical domain before details of the solution is known.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] So the grid may or may not be the best for the given problem.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Adaptive methods are used to improve the accuracy of the solutions.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The adaptive method is referred to as ‘h’ method if mesh refinement is used, ‘r’ method if the number of grid point is fixed and not redistributed and ‘p’ if the order of solution scheme is increased in finite-element theory.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The multi dimensional problems using the equidistribution scheme can be accomplished in several ways.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The simplest to understand are the Poisson Grid Generators with control function based on the equidistribution of the weight function with the diffusion set as a multiple of desired cell volume.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The equidistribution scheme can also be applied to the unstructured problem.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The problem is the connectivity hampers if mesh point movement is very large.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Steady flow and the time-accurate flow calculation can be solved through this adaptive method.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The grid is refined and after a predetermined number of iteration in order to adapt it in a steady flow problem.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The grid will stop adjusting to the changes once the solution converges.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In time accurate case coupling of the partial differential equations of the physical problem and those describing the grid movement is required.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Image-based meshing is the automated process of creating computer models for computational fluid dynamics (CFD) and finite element analysis (FEA) from 3D image data (such as magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), computed tomography (CT) or microtomography).
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Although a wide range of mesh generation techniques are currently available, these were usually developed to generate models from computer-aided design (CAD), and therefore have difficulties meshing from 3D imaging data.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Recent advances in artificial intelligence (AI) and machine learning (ML) have significantly impacted mesh generation, automating traditionally labor-intensive processes and improving accuracy in computational simulations.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] AI-driven techniques, such as neural networks and reinforcement learning, can predict optimal mesh configurations, adaptively refine meshes, and reduce manual intervention in finite element analysis (FEA) and computational fluid dynamics (CFD).
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Companies like NVIDIA, Ansys, and Siemens have integrated AI-based mesh generation tools into their simulation software, accelerating workflows in aerospace, automotive, and biomedical engineering.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Usually the cells are polygonal or polyhedral and form a mesh that partitions the domain.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Important classes of two-dimensional elements include triangles (simplices) and quadrilaterals (topological squares).
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In three-dimensions the most-common cells are tetrahedra (simplices) and hexahedra (topological cubes).
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Simplicial meshes may be of any dimension and include triangles (2D) and tetrahedra (3D) as important instances.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] *Cubical meshes* is the pan-dimensional category that includes quads (2D) and hexes (3D).
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In 3D, 4-sided pyramids and 3-sided prisms appear in conformal meshes of mixed cell type.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The mesh is embedded in a geometric space that is typically two or three dimensional, although sometimes the dimension is increased by one by adding the time-dimension.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Higher dimensional meshes are used in niche contexts.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] One-dimensional meshes are useful as well.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] A significant category is surface meshes, which are 2D meshes embedded in 3D to represent a curved surface.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Dual graphs have several roles in meshing.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] One can make a polyhedral Voronoi diagram mesh by dualizing a Delaunay triangulation simplicial mesh.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] One can create a cubical mesh by generating an arrangement of surfaces and dualizing the intersection graph; see spatial twist continuum.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Sometimes both the primal mesh and its dual mesh are used in the same simulation; see Hodge star operator.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] This arises from physics involving divergence and curl operators, such as flux and vorticity or electricity & magnetism, where one variable naturally lives on the primal faces and its counterpart on the dual faces.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Three-dimensional meshes created for finite element analysis need to consist of tetrahedra, pyramids, prisms or hexahedra.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Those used for the finite volume method can consist of arbitrary polyhedra.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Those used for finite difference methods consist of piecewise structured arrays of hexahedra known as multi-block structured meshes.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] 4-sided pyramids are useful to conformally connect hexes to tets.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] 3-sided prisms are used for boundary layers conforming to a tet mesh of the far-interior of the object.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Surface meshes are useful in computer graphics where the surfaces of objects reflect light (also subsurface scattering) and a full 3D mesh is not needed.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Surface meshes are also used to model thin objects such as sheet metal in auto manufacturing and building exteriors in architecture.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] High (e.g., 17) dimensional cubical meshes are common in astrophysics and string theory.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] What is the precise definition of a *mesh?* There is not a universally-accepted mathematical description that applies in all contexts.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] However, some mathematical objects are clearly meshes: a simplicial complex is a mesh composed of simplices.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Most polyhedral (e.g. cubical) meshes are *conformal,* meaning they have the cell structure of a CW complex, a generalization of a simplicial complex.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] A mesh need not be simplicial because an arbitrary subset of nodes of a cell is not necessarily a cell: e.g., three nodes of a quad does not define a cell.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] However, two cells intersect at cells: e.g. a quad does not have a node in its interior.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The intersection of two cells may be several cells: e.g., two quads may share two edges.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] An intersection being more than one cell is sometimes forbidden and rarely desired; the goal of some mesh improvement techniques (e.g. pillowing) is to remove these configurations.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In some contexts, a distinction is made between a topological mesh and a geometric mesh whose embedding satisfies certain quality criteria.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Important mesh variants that are not CW complexes include non-conformal meshes where cells do not meet strictly face-to-face, but the cells nonetheless partition the domain.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] An example of this is an octree, where an element face may be partitioned by the faces of adjacent elements.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Such meshes are useful for flux-based simulations.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In overset grids, there are multiple conformal meshes that overlap geometrically and do not partition the domain; see e.g., Overflow, the OVERset grid FLOW solver.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] So-called meshless or meshfree methods often make use of some mesh-like discretization of the domain, and have basis functions with overlapping support.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Sometimes a local mesh is created near each simulation degree-of-freedom point, and these meshes may overlap and be non-conformal to one another.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Implicit triangulations are based on a delta complex: for each triangle the lengths of its edges, and a gluing map between face edges.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Many meshes use linear elements, where the mapping from the abstract to realized element is linear, and mesh edges are straight segments.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Higher order polynomial mappings are common, especially quadratic.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] A primary goal for higher-order elements is to more accurately represent the domain boundary, although they have accuracy benefits in the interior of the mesh as well.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] One of the motivations for cubical meshes is that linear cubical elements have some of the same numerical advantages as quadratic simplicial elements.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In the isogeometric analysis simulation technique, the mesh cells containing the domain boundary use the CAD representation directly instead of a linear or polynomial approximation.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Improving a mesh involves changing its discrete connectivity, the continuous geometric position of its cells, or both.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] For discrete changes, for simplicial elements one swaps edges and inserts/removes nodes.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The same kinds of operations are done for cubical (quad/hex) meshes, although there are fewer possible operations and local changes have global consequences.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] E.g., for a hexahedral mesh, merging two nodes creates cells that are not hexes, but if diagonally-opposite nodes on a quadrilateral are merged and this is propagated into collapsing an entire face-connected column of hexes, then all remaining cells will still be hexes.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] In adaptive mesh refinement, elements are split (h-refinement) in areas where the function being calculated has a high gradient.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Meshes are also coarsened, removing elements for efficiency.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The multigrid method does something similar to refinement and coarsening to speed up the numerical solve, but without actually changing the mesh.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] For continuous changes, nodes are moved, or the higher-dimensional faces are moved by changing the polynomial order of elements.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Moving nodes to improve quality is called "smoothing" or "r-refinement" and increasing the order of elements is called "p-refinement." Nodes are also moved in simulations where the shape of objects change over time.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] This degrades the shape of the elements.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] If the object deforms enough, the entire object is remeshed and the current solution mapped from the old mesh to the new mesh.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] The field is highly interdisciplinary, with contributions found in mathematics, computer science, and engineering.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Meshing R&D is distinguished by an equal focus on discrete and continuous math and computation, as with computational geometry, but in contrast to graph theory (discrete) and numerical analysis (continuous).
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Mesh generation is deceptively difficult: it is easy for humans to see how to create a mesh of a given object, but difficult to program a computer to make good decisions for arbitrary input a priori.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] There is an infinite variety of geometry found in nature and man-made objects.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Many mesh generation researchers were first users of meshes.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Mesh generation continues to receive widespread attention, support and funding because the human-time to create a mesh dwarfs the time to set up and solve the calculation once the mesh is finished.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] Meshing research is published in a broad range of journals.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] This is in keeping with the interdisciplinary nature of the research required to make progress, and also the wide variety of applications that make use of meshes.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] About 150 meshing publications appear each year across 20 journals, with at most 20 publications appearing in any one journal.
[src:finite-element-method/mesh-generation] There is no journal whose primary topic is meshing.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] In the finite element method for the numerical solution of elliptic partial differential equations, the **stiffness matrix** is a matrix that represents the system of linear equations that must be solved in order to ascertain an approximate solution to the differential equation.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] on some domain Ω, subject to the boundary condition *u* = 0 on the boundary of Ω.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] To discretize this equation by the finite element method, one chooses a set of *basis functions* {*φ*1, …, *φn*} defined on Ω which also vanish on the boundary.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] as a consequence of the homogenous Dirichlet boundary conditions.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] By defining the *load vector* **F** with components ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} _{i}=\int _{\Omega }\varphi _{i}f\,dx,}$ the coefficients ui are determined by the linear system **Au** = **F**.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] **A***ij* = **A***ji*, so all its eigenvalues are real.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] Moreover, it is a strictly positive-definite matrix, so that the system **Au** = **F** always has a unique solution.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] Note that the stiffness matrix will be different depending on the computational grid used for the domain and what type of finite element is used.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] For example, the stiffness matrix when piecewise quadratic finite elements are used will have more degrees of freedom than piecewise linear elements.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] Determining the stiffness matrix for other PDEs follows essentially the same procedure, but it can be complicated by the choice of boundary conditions.
