[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] The coefficients ui are still found by solving a system of linear equations, but the matrix representing the system is markedly different from that for the ordinary Poisson problem.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] In order to implement the finite element method on a computer, one must first choose a set of basis functions and then compute the integrals defining the stiffness matrix.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] Usually, the domain Ω is discretized by some form of mesh generation, wherein it is divided into non-overlapping triangles or quadrilaterals, which are generally referred to as elements.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] The basis functions are then chosen to be polynomials of some order within each element, and continuous across element boundaries.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] The simplest choices are piecewise linear for triangular elements and piecewise bilinear for rectangular elements.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] The element stiffness matrix is zero for most values of i and j, for which the corresponding basis functions are zero within Tk.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] The full stiffness matrix **A** is the sum of the element stiffness matrices.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] In particular, for basis functions that are only supported locally, the stiffness matrix is sparse.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] For many standard choices of basis functions, i.e. piecewise linear basis functions on triangles, there are simple formulas for the element stiffness matrices.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] When the differential equation is more complicated, say by having an inhomogeneous diffusion coefficient, the integral defining the element stiffness matrix can be evaluated by Gaussian quadrature.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] The condition number of the stiffness matrix depends strongly on the quality of the numerical grid.
[src:finite-element-method/stiffness-matrix] In particular, triangles with small angles in the finite element mesh induce large eigenvalues of the stiffness matrix, degrading the solution quality.
[src:finite-element-method/weak-formulation] The **Lax–Milgram theorem**, named after Peter Lax and Arthur Milgram who proved it in 1954, provides weak formulations for certain systems on Hilbert spaces.
